Philosophy, science and religion are three endeavours that shape in fundamental ways of how we think, what we value, and how we live. This report aims to explore different philosophers’ views on religion and science - how much did they care about and how was their attitudes towards them.

The dataset philosophy_data I used in this project is from kaggle website which compiles over 300,000 sentences from over 50 texts spanning 10 major schools of philosophy. Luckily, most of the text data were already cleaned so that we can use them directly and easily.

Part 1: Philosophy and Religion

First of all, I extract and analyze the philosophical text which are related to religion from the dataset. To filter out those data, I use grepl() to search for the keywords – god, gods, religion, religious, theology, theological – in each sentence from each row. By using this method, we find out a total of 8791 rows from our dataset. Grantedly, it is not a fully exhaustive way to find out all the religion-related text, but we think those data are big enough for us to conduct further text analysis. (This religion-filtered data is uploaded to the output file as ‘religion.csv’)

Question 1.1: Which schools mention the idea of religion frequently?

To answer this question, I count the number of sentences related to the idea of religion by each school and sort them in a descending order.

From the bar plot below, we can easily see that Rationalism, Plato, German_idealism, Continental and Nietzsche are the top 5 schools which have more than 500 entries of text data related to religion. Therefore, if someone wants to know more about the religion idea in philosophy, we could recomend him or her to read those schools’ books based on our observation.

Question 1.2: Which schools have more positive attitude towards religion? Which schools are more negative?

I try to answer this question by using the NRC sentimental analysis. This package helps to count and categorize the words as “positive” and “negative”. I define the positive ratio as the percentage of positive words appeared in each schools’ text and recenter the ratio at 50% level. In other words, if the value of a certain school is above 0, it tends to be positive towards the religion idea, and the bigger the number is, the more positive its attitude is. And vice versa.

From the bar chart below, we can see that Rationalism seems to hold the most positive attitude – its value is around 0.12, meaning that ~62% of the text showing positiveness. On the other hand, Communism is in general more negative with only ~41% test showing positiveness.

Question 1.3: Explore Sentiment on the word level.

According to our result in 1.2, I decide to take a deeper look into the two extreme schools – rationalism, which is the most positive one, and communism, which is the most negative one. I try to analyze their sentiment by using wordcloud to see what words are used frequently when these two schools describe religion. I also compare and visualize the top n words for each sentiment by using the bar charts as shown below.

For Rationalism, words frequently appeared in the text are something like “love”, “good”, “wisdom” and “perfect”, implying that rationalists believe God plays an active and effective role in human life. Even for the negative words like “evil” and “sin”, they are more about describing the idea from Christianity rather than expressing criticism. Besides, we can also see that the positive words have shown up much more often than the negative words if we take a look at the x axis of the barplot, meaning that rationalism overall holds a very positive perspective towards religion.

For Communism, most of the words, no matter positive ones or negative ones, are related to politics (e.g. “political”, “laws”, “revolunary”) and labors (e.g. “labour”, “peasantry”, “work”), trying to criticize that religion is used as a tool to suppress pople and exploit labor forces by dictators.
